# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: ito-calculus
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] The central concept is the Itô stochastic integral, a stochastic generalization of the Riemann–Stieltjes integral in analysis.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] The integrands and the integrators are now stochastic processes: $Y_{t}=\int _{0}^{t}H_{s}\,dX_{s},$ where *H* is a locally square-integrable process adapted to the filtration generated by *X* (Revuz & Yor 1999, Chapter IV), which is a Brownian motion or, more generally, a semimartingale.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] The result of the integration is then another stochastic process.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] Concretely, the integral from 0 to any particular t is a random variable, defined as a limit of a certain sequence of random variables.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] The paths of Brownian motion fail to satisfy the requirements to be able to apply the standard techniques of calculus.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] So with the integrand a stochastic process, the Itô stochastic integral amounts to an integral with respect to a function which is not differentiable at any point and has infinite variation over every time interval.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] The main insight is that the integral can be defined as long as the integrand *H* is adapted, which loosely speaking means that its value at time t can only depend on information available up until this time.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] Roughly speaking, one chooses a sequence of partitions of the interval from 0 to t and constructs Riemann sums.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] Every time we are computing a Riemann sum, we are using a particular instantiation of the integrator.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] It is crucial which point in each of the small intervals is used to compute the value of the function.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] The limit then is taken in probability as the mesh of the partition is going to zero.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] Numerous technical details have to be taken care of to show that this limit exists and is independent of the particular sequence of partitions.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] Typically, the left end of the interval is used.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] Important results of Itô calculus include the integration by parts formula and Itô's lemma, which is a change of variables formula.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] These differ from the formulas of standard calculus, due to quadratic variation terms.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] This can be contrasted to the Stratonovich integral as an alternative formulation; it does follow the chain rule, and does not require Itô's lemma.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] The two integral forms can be converted to one-another.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] The Stratonovich integral is obtained as the limiting form of a Riemann sum that employs the average of stochastic variable over each small timestep, whereas the Itô integral considers it only at the beginning.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] In mathematical finance, the described evaluation strategy of the integral is conceptualized as that we are first deciding what to do, then observing the change in the prices.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] The integrand is how much stock we hold, the integrator represents the movement of the prices, and the integral is how much money we have in total including what our stock is worth, at any given moment.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] The prices of stocks and other traded financial assets can be modeled by stochastic processes such as Brownian motion or, more often, geometric Brownian motion (see Black–Scholes).
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] Then, the Itô stochastic integral represents the payoff of a continuous-time trading strategy consisting of holding an amount *Ht* of the stock at time *t*.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] In this situation, the condition that *H* is adapted corresponds to the necessary restriction that the trading strategy can only make use of the available information at any time.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] This prevents the possibility of unlimited gains through clairvoyance: buying the stock just before each uptick in the market and selling before each downtick.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] Similarly, the condition that *H* is adapted implies that the stochastic integral will not diverge when calculated as a limit of Riemann sums (Revuz & Yor 1999, Chapter IV).
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] The process *Y* defined before as $Y_{t}=\int _{0}^{t}H\,dX\equiv \int _{0}^{t}H_{s}\,dX_{s},$ is itself a stochastic process with time parameter *t*, which is also sometimes written as *Y* = *H* · *X* (Rogers & Williams 2000).
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] Alternatively, the integral is often written in differential form *dY* = *H* *dX*, which is equivalent to *Y* − *Y*0 = *H* · *X*.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] A Brownian motion *B* is understood to be an ${\mathcal {F}}_{t}$ -Brownian motion, which is just a standard Brownian motion with the properties that *B**t* is ${\mathcal {F}}_{t}$ -measurable and that *B**t*+*s* − *B**t* is independent of ${\mathcal {F}}_{t}$ for all *s*,*t* ≥ 0 (Revuz & Yor 1999).
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] The Itô integral can be defined in a manner similar to the Riemann–Stieltjes integral, that is as a limit in probability of Riemann sums; such a limit does not necessarily exist pathwise.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] Suppose that *B* is a Wiener process (Brownian motion) and that *H* is a right-continuous (càdlàg), adapted and locally bounded process.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] It can be shown that this limit converges in probability.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] For some applications, such as martingale representation theorems and local times, the integral is needed for processes that are not continuous.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] The predictable processes form the smallest class that is closed under taking limits of sequences and contains all adapted left-continuous processes.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] If *H* is any predictable process such that ∫0*t* *H*2 *ds* < ∞ for every *t* ≥ 0 then the integral of *H* with respect to *B* can be defined, and *H* is said to be *B*-integrable.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] Any such process can be approximated by a sequence *Hn* of left-continuous, adapted and locally bounded processes, in the sense that $\int _{0}^{t}(H-H_{n})^{2}\,ds\to 0$ in probability.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] Then, the Itô integral is $\int _{0}^{t}H\,dB=\lim _{n\to \infty }\int _{0}^{t}H_{n}\,dB$ where, again, the limit can be shown to converge in probability.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] The stochastic integral satisfies the Itô isometry $\mathbb {E} \left[\left(\int _{0}^{t}H_{s}\,dB_{s}\right)^{2}\right]=\mathbb {E} \left[\int _{0}^{t}H_{s}^{2}\,ds\right]$ which holds when *H* is bounded or, more generally, when the integral on the right hand side is finite.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] Here, *B* is a Brownian motion and it is required that σ is a predictable *B*-integrable process, and μ is predictable and (Lebesgue) integrable.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] This is defined for all locally bounded and predictable integrands.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] More generally, it is required that *Hσ* be *B*-integrable and *Hμ* be Lebesgue integrable, so that $\int _{0}^{t}\left(H^{2}\sigma ^{2}+|H\mu |\right)ds<\infty .$ Such predictable processes *H* are called *X*-integrable.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] An important result for the study of Itô processes is Itô's lemma.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] This is the stochastic calculus version of the change of variables formula and chain rule.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] It differs from the standard result due to the additional term involving the second derivative of *f*, which comes from the property that Brownian motion has non-zero quadratic variation.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] The Itô integral is defined with respect to a semimartingale *X*.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] These are processes which can be decomposed as *X* = *M* + *A* for a local martingale *M* and finite variation process *A*.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] Important examples of such processes include Brownian motion, which is a martingale, and Lévy processes.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] For a left continuous, locally bounded and adapted process *H* the integral *H* · *X* exists, and can be calculated as a limit of Riemann sums.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] The stochastic integral of left-continuous processes is general enough for studying much of stochastic calculus.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] For example, it is sufficient for applications of Itô's Lemma, changes of measure via Girsanov's theorem, and for the study of stochastic differential equations.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] However, it is inadequate for other important topics such as martingale representation theorems and local times.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] The integral extends to all predictable and locally bounded integrands, in a unique way, such that the dominated convergence theorem holds.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] The uniqueness of the extension from left-continuous to predictable integrands is a result of the monotone class lemma.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] In general, the stochastic integral *H* · *X* can be defined even in cases where the predictable process *H* is not locally bounded.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] Associativity of stochastic integration implies that *H* is *X*-integrable, with integral *H* · *X* = *Y*, if and only if *Y*0 = 0 and *K* · *Y* = (*KH*) · *X*.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] The set of *X*-integrable processes is denoted by *L*(*X*).
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] As with ordinary calculus, integration by parts is an important result in stochastic calculus.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] The integration by parts formula for the Itô integral differs from the standard result due to the inclusion of a quadratic covariation term.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] This term comes from the fact that Itô calculus deals with processes with non-zero quadratic variation, which only occurs for infinite variation processes (such as Brownian motion).
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] The result is similar to the integration by parts theorem for the Riemann–Stieltjes integral but has an additional quadratic variation term.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] Itô's lemma is the version of the chain rule or change of variables formula which applies to the Itô integral.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] It is one of the most powerful and frequently used theorems in stochastic calculus.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] The formula can be generalized to include an explicit time-dependence in $f,$ and in other ways (see Itô's lemma).
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] An important property of the Itô integral is that it preserves the local martingale property.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] If *M* is a local martingale and *H* is a locally bounded predictable process then *H* · *M* is also a local martingale.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] For integrands which are not locally bounded, there are examples where *H* · *M* is not a local martingale.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] However, this can only occur when *M* is not continuous.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] If *M* is a continuous local martingale then a predictable process *H* is *M*-integrable if and only if $\int _{0}^{t}H^{2}\,d[M]<\infty ,$ for each t, and *H* · *M* is always a local martingale.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] The most general statement for a discontinuous local martingale *M* is that if (*H*2 · [*M*])1/2 is locally integrable then *H* · *M* exists and is a local martingale.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] For bounded integrands, the Itô stochastic integral preserves the space of *square integrable* martingales, which is the set of càdlàg martingales *M* such that E[*M**t*2] is finite for all t.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] The Itô isometry is often used as an important step in the construction of the stochastic integral, by defining *H* · *M* to be the unique extension of this isometry from a certain class of simple integrands to all bounded and predictable processes.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] For any *p* > 1, and bounded predictable integrand, the stochastic integral preserves the space of *p*-integrable martingales.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] These are càdlàg martingales such that E(|*Mt*|*p*) is finite for all t.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] However, this is not always true in the case where *p* = 1.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] There are examples of integrals of bounded predictable processes with respect to martingales which are not themselves martingales.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] The maximum process of a càdlàg process *M* is written as *M*t* = sup*s* ≤*t* |*Ms*|.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] For any *p* ≥ 1 and bounded predictable integrand, the stochastic integral preserves the space of càdlàg martingales *M* such that E[(*M*t*)*p*] is finite for all t.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] If *p* > 1 then this is the same as the space of *p*-integrable martingales, by Doob's inequalities.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] These are used to show that if (*M*t*)*p* is integrable and *H* is a bounded predictable process then $\mathbb {E} \left[((H\cdot M)_{t}^{*})^{p}\right]\leq C\mathbb {E} \left[(H^{2}\cdot [M]_{t})^{\frac {p}{2}}\right]<\infty$ and, consequently, *H* · *M* is a *p*-integrable martingale.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] More generally, this statement is true whenever (*H*2 · [*M*])*p*/2 is integrable.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] Proofs that the Itô integral is well defined typically proceed by first looking at very simple integrands, such as piecewise constant, left continuous and adapted processes where the integral can be written explicitly.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] It can then be extended to all *B*-integrable processes by localization.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] This method allows the integral to be defined with respect to any Itô process.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] For a general semimartingale *X*, the decomposition *X* = *M* + *A* into a local martingale *M* plus a finite variation process *A* can be used.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] Then, the integral can be shown to exist separately with respect to *M* and *A* and combined using linearity, *H* · *X* = *H* · *M* + *H* · *A*, to get the integral with respect to *X*.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] The standard Lebesgue–Stieltjes integral allows integration to be defined with respect to finite variation processes, so the existence of the Itô integral for semimartingales will follow from any construction for local martingales.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] For a càdlàg square integrable martingale *M*, a generalized form of the Itô isometry can be used.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] First, the Doob–Meyer decomposition theorem is used to show that a decomposition *M*2 = *N* + ⟨*M*⟩ exists, where *N* is a martingale and ⟨*M*⟩ is a right-continuous, increasing and predictable process starting at zero.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] This uniquely defines ⟨*M*⟩, which is referred to as the *predictable quadratic variation* of *M*.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] The Itô isometry for square integrable martingales is then $\mathbb {E} \left[(H\cdot M_{t})^{2}\right]=\mathbb {E} \left[\int _{0}^{t}H_{s}^{2}\,d\langle M\rangle _{s}\right],$ which can be proved directly for simple predictable integrands.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] As with the case above for Brownian motion, a continuous linear extension can be used to uniquely extend to all predictable integrands satisfying *E*[*H*2 · ⟨*M*⟩*t*] < ∞.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] This method can be extended to all local square integrable martingales by localization.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] Finally, the Doob–Meyer decomposition can be used to decompose any local martingale into the sum of a local square integrable martingale and a finite variation process, allowing the Itô integral to be constructed with respect to any semimartingale.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] The latter applies directly to local martingales without having to first deal with the square integrable martingale case.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] Alternative proofs exist only making use of the fact that *X* is càdlàg, adapted, and the set {*H* · *Xt*: |*H*| ≤ 1 is simple previsible} is bounded in probability for each time *t*, which is an alternative definition for *X* to be a semimartingale.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] A continuous linear extension can be used to construct the integral for all left-continuous and adapted integrands with right limits everywhere (caglad or L-processes).
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] This is general enough to be able to apply techniques such as Itô's lemma (Protter 2004).
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] Also, a Khintchine inequality can be used to prove the dominated convergence theorem and extend the integral to general predictable integrands (Bichteler 2002).
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] The Itô calculus is first and foremost defined as an integral calculus as outlined above.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] Malliavin calculus provides a theory of differentiation for random variables defined over Wiener space, including an integration by parts formula (Nualart 2006).
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] This representation theorem can be interpreted formally as saying that α is the "time derivative" of *M* with respect to Brownian motion *B*, since α is precisely the process that must be integrated up to time t to obtain *M**t* − *M*0, as in deterministic calculus.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] In physics, usually stochastic differential equations (SDEs), such as Langevin equations, are used, rather than stochastic integrals.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] Here an Itô stochastic differential equation (SDE) is often formulated via ${\dot {x}}_{k}=h_{k}+g_{kl}\xi _{l},$ where $\xi _{j}$ is Gaussian white noise with $\langle \xi _{k}(t_{1})\,\xi _{l}(t_{2})\rangle =\delta _{kl}\delta (t_{1}-t_{2})$ and Einstein's summation convention is used.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] SDEs frequently occur in physics in Stratonovich form, as limits of stochastic differential equations driven by colored noise if the correlation time of the noise term approaches zero.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-calculus] For a recent treatment of different interpretations of stochastic differential equations see for example (Lau & Lubensky 2007).
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] In mathematics – specifically, in stochastic analysis – an **Itô diffusion** is a solution to a specific type of stochastic differential equation.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] That equation is similar to the Langevin equation used in physics to describe the Brownian motion of a particle subjected to a potential in a viscous fluid.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] Itô diffusions are named after the Japanese mathematician Kiyosi Itô.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] for some constant *C* and all *x*, *y* ∈ **R***n*; this condition ensures the existence of a unique strong solution *X* to the stochastic differential equation given above.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] The vector field *b* is known as the **drift coefficient** of *X*; the matrix field σ is known as the **diffusion coefficient** of *X*.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] *b* and σ do not depend upon time; if they were, *X* would be referred to only as an *Itô process*, not a diffusion.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] In particular, an Itô diffusion is a continuous, strongly Markovian process such that the domain of its characteristic operator includes all twice-continuously differentiable functions, so it is a *diffusion* in the sense defined by Dynkin (1965).
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] An Itô diffusion *X* is a sample continuous process, i.e., for almost all realisations *Bt*(ω) of the noise, *Xt*(ω) is a continuous function of the time parameter, *t*.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] This follows from the standard existence and uniqueness theory for strong solutions of stochastic differential equations.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] In addition to being (sample) continuous, an Itô diffusion *X* satisfies the stronger requirement to be a Feller-continuous process.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] For a point *x* ∈ **R***n*, let **P***x* denote the law of *X* given initial datum *X*0 = *x*, and let **E***x* denote expectation with respect to **P***x*.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] The behaviour of the function *u* above when the time *t* is varied is addressed by the Kolmogorov backward equation, the Fokker–Planck equation, etc.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] An Itô diffusion *X* has the important property of being *Markovian*: the future behaviour of *X*, given what has happened up to some time *t*, is the same as if the process had been started at the position *Xt* at time 0.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] It is easy to show that *X* is adapted to Σ∗ (i.e. each *Xt* is Σ*t*-measurable), so the natural filtration *F*∗ = *F*∗*X* of (Ω, Σ) generated by *X* has *Ft* ⊆ Σ*t* for each *t* ≥ 0.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] Let *f* : **R***n* → **R** be a bounded, Borel-measurable function.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] The strong Markov property is a generalization of the Markov property above in which *t* is replaced by a suitable random time τ : Ω → [0, +∞] known as a stopping time.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] So, for example, rather than "restarting" the process *X* at time *t* = 1, one could "restart" whenever *X* first reaches some specified point *p* of **R***n*.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] As before, let *f* : **R***n* → **R** be a bounded, Borel-measurable function.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] Let τ be a stopping time with respect to the filtration Σ∗ with τ < +∞ almost surely.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] Associated to each Itô diffusion, there is a second-order partial differential operator known as the *generator* of the diffusion.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] The generator is very useful in many applications and encodes a great deal of information about the process *X*.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] The set of all functions *f* for which this limit exists at a point *x* is denoted *DA*(*x*), while *DA* denotes the set of all *f* for which the limit exists for all *x* ∈ **R***n*.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] i.e., *A* = Δ/2, where Δ denotes the Laplace operator.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] The generator is used in the formulation of Kolmogorov's backward equation.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] Intuitively, this equation tells us how the expected value of any suitably smooth statistic of *X* evolves in time: it must solve a certain partial differential equation in which time *t* and the initial position *x* are the independent variables.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] The Fokker–Planck equation (also known as *Kolmogorov's forward equation*) is in some sense the "adjoint" to the backward equation, and tells us how the probability density functions of *Xt* evolve with time *t*.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] Let *A*∗ denote the Hermitian adjoint of *A* (with respect to the *L*2 inner product).
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] The Feynman–Kac formula is a useful generalization of Kolmogorov's backward equation.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] Again, *f* is in *C*2(**R***n*; **R**) and has compact support, and *q* : **R***n* → **R** is taken to be a continuous function that is bounded below.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] Moreover, if *w* : [0, +∞) × **R***n* → **R** is *C*1 in time, *C*2 in space, bounded on *K* × **R***n* for all compact *K*, and satisfies the above partial differential equation, then *w* must be *v* as defined above.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] Kolmogorov's backward equation is the special case of the Feynman–Kac formula in which *q*(*x*) = 0 for all *x* ∈ **R***n*.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] The characteristic operator of an Itô diffusion *X* is a partial differential operator closely related to the generator, but somewhat more general.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] It is more suited to certain problems, for example in the solution of the Dirichlet problem.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] is the first exit time from *U* for *X*. $D_{\mathcal {A}}$ denotes the set of all *f* for which this limit exists for all *x* ∈ **R***n* and all sequences {*Uk*}.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] The characteristic operator and infinitesimal generator are very closely related, and even agree for a large class of functions.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] Above, the generator (and hence characteristic operator) of Brownian motion on **R***n* was calculated to be ⁠1/2⁠Δ, where Δ denotes the Laplace operator.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] where [*gij*] = [*gij*]−1 in the sense of the inverse of a square matrix.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] In general, the generator *A* of an Itô diffusion *X* is not a bounded operator.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] However, if a positive multiple of the identity operator **I** is subtracted from *A* then the resulting operator is invertible.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] The inverse of this operator can be expressed in terms of *X* itself using the resolvent operator.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] It can be shown, using the Feller continuity of the diffusion *X*, that *R*α*g* is itself a bounded, continuous function.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] Sometimes it is necessary to find an invariant measure for an Itô diffusion *X*, i.e. a measure on **R***n* that does not change under the "flow" of *X*: i.e., if *X*0 is distributed according to such an invariant measure μ∞, then *Xt* is also distributed according to μ∞ for any *t* ≥ 0.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] This illustrates one of the connections between stochastic analysis and the study of partial differential equations.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] where β > 0 plays the role of an inverse temperature and Ψ : **R***n* → **R** is a scalar potential satisfying suitable smoothness and growth conditions.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] In this case, the Fokker–Planck equation has a unique stationary solution ρ∞ (i.e.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] is the negative of the Gibbs-Boltzmann entropy functional.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] Even when the potential Ψ is not well-behaved enough for the partition function *Z* and the Gibbs measure μ∞ to be defined, the free energy *F*[ρ(*t*, ·)] still makes sense for each time *t* ≥ 0, provided that the initial condition has *F*[ρ(0, ·)] < +∞.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] The free energy functional *F* is, in fact, a Lyapunov function for the Fokker–Planck equation: *F*[ρ(*t*, ·)] must decrease as *t* increases.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] Thus, *F* is an *H*-function for the *X*-dynamics.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] where *m* ∈ **R***n* and β, κ > 0 are given constants.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] Heuristically, for large *t*, *Xt* is approximately normally distributed with mean *m* and variance (βκ)−1.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] In general, an Itô diffusion *X* is not a martingale.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] where *A* is the generator of *X*, is a martingale with respect to the natural filtration *F*∗ of (Ω, Σ) by *X*.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] Dynkin's formula, named after Eugene Dynkin, gives the expected value of any suitably smooth statistic of an Itô diffusion *X* (with generator *A*) at a stopping time.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] Dynkin's formula can be used to calculate many useful statistics of stopping times.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] Dynkin's formula provides information about the behaviour of *X* at a fairly general stopping time.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] For more information on the distribution of *X* at a hitting time, one can study the *harmonic measure* of the process.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] In many situations, it is sufficient to know when an Itô diffusion *X* will first leave a measurable set *H* ⊆ **R***n*.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] Sometimes, however, one also wishes to know the distribution of the points at which *X* exits the set.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] For example, canonical Brownian motion *B* on the real line starting at 0 exits the interval (−1, 1) at −1 with probability ⁠1/2⁠ and at 1 with probability ⁠1/2⁠, so *B*τ(−1, 1) is uniformly distributed on the set {−1, 1}.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] The mean value property is very useful in the solution of partial differential equations using stochastic processes.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] Let *A* be a partial differential operator on a domain *D* ⊆ **R***n* and let *X* be an Itô diffusion with *A* as its generator.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] Intuitively, the Green measure of a Borel set *H* is the expected length of time that *X* stays in *H* before it leaves the domain *D*.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-diffusion] where *G*(*x*, *y*) is Green's function for the operator ⁠1/2⁠Δ on the domain *D*.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-s-lemma] In mathematics, **Itô's lemma** or **Itô's formula** (also called the **Itô–Doeblin formula**) is an identity used in Itô calculus to find the differential of a time-dependent function of a stochastic process.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-s-lemma] It serves as the stochastic calculus counterpart of the chain rule.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-s-lemma] It can be heuristically derived by forming the Taylor series expansion of the function up to its second derivatives and retaining terms up to first order in the time increment and second order in the Wiener process increment.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-s-lemma] The lemma is widely employed in mathematical finance, and its best known application is in the derivation of the Black–Scholes equation for option values.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-s-lemma] This result was discovered by Japanese mathematician Kiyoshi Itô in 1951.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-s-lemma] Suppose we are given the stochastic differential equation $dX_{t}=\mu _{t}\ dt+\sigma _{t}\ dB_{t},$ where *B**t* is a Wiener process and the functions $\mu _{t},\sigma _{t}$ are deterministic (not stochastic) functions of time.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-s-lemma] This expression lets us easily read off the mean and variance of $X_{t}$ (which has no higher moments).
[src:ito-calculus/itô-s-lemma] However, sometimes we are faced with a stochastic differential equation for a more complex process $Y_{t},$ in which the process appears on both sides of the differential equation.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-s-lemma] That is, say $dY_{t}=a_{1}(Y_{t},t)\ dt+a_{2}(Y_{t},t)\ dB_{t},$ for some functions $a_{1}$ and $a_{2}.$ In this case, we cannot immediately write a formal solution as we did for the simpler case above.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-s-lemma] Instead, we hope to write the process $Y_{t}$ as a function of a simpler process $X_{t}$ taking the form above.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-s-lemma] That is, we want to identify three functions $f(t,x),\mu _{t},$ and $\sigma _{t},$ such that $Y_{t}=f(t,X_{t})$ and $dX_{t}=\mu _{t}\ dt+\sigma _{t}\ dB_{t}.$ In practice, Ito's lemma is used in order to find this transformation.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-s-lemma] Finally, once we have transformed the problem into the simpler type of problem, we can determine the mean and higher moments of the process.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-s-lemma] We derive Itô's lemma by expanding a Taylor series and applying the rules of stochastic calculus.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-s-lemma] Suppose we know that $X_{t},X_{t+dt}$ are two jointly-Gaussian distributed random variables, and f is nonlinear but has a continuous second derivative, then in general, neither of $f(X_{t}),f(X_{t+dt})$ is Gaussian, and their joint distribution is also not Gaussian.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-s-lemma] However, since $X_{t+dt}\mid X_{t}$ is Gaussian, we might still find $f(X_{t+dt})\mid f(X_{t})$ is Gaussian.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-s-lemma] This is not true when $dt$ is finite, but when $dt$ becomes infinitesimal, this becomes true.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-s-lemma] The key idea is that $X_{t+dt}=X_{t}+\mu _{t}\,dt+dW_{t}$ has a deterministic part and a noisy part.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-s-lemma] When f is nonlinear, the noisy part has a deterministic contribution.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-s-lemma] If f is convex, then the deterministic contribution is positive (by Jensen's inequality).
[src:ito-calculus/itô-s-lemma] The random part is non-Gaussian, but the non-Gaussian parts decay faster than the Gaussian part, and at the $dt\to 0$ limit, only the Gaussian part remains.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-s-lemma] To understand why there should be a contribution due to convexity, consider the simplest case of geometric Brownian walk (of the stock market): $S_{t+dt}=S_{t}(1+dB_{t})$ .
[src:ito-calculus/itô-s-lemma] However, although the expectation of $X_{t}$ remains constant, the expectation of $S_{t}$ grows.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-s-lemma] Intuitively it is because the downside is limited at zero, but the upside is unlimited.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-s-lemma] That is, while $X_{t}$ is normally distributed, $S_{t}$ is log-normally distributed.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-s-lemma] In the following subsections we discuss versions of Itô's lemma for different types of stochastic processes.
[src:ito-calculus/itô-s-lemma] This immediately implies that *f*(*t*,*X**t*) is itself an Itô drift-diffusion process.
